Let's work through each ratio step-by-step.

1. Return on Equity (ROE)

ROE is calculated by dividing the Net Profit by the average Owner’s Equity. Here the Owner’s Equity on the balance sheet is:
• Initial Owner’s Equity = Paid-in Capital (since Retained Earnings are 0) = 13,000,000.00  
• Ending Owner’s Equity = 14,105,265.77  

The average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 14,105,265.77) / 2  
  = 27,105,265.77 / 2  
  ≈ 13,552,632.89

Net Profit from the income statement = 1,105,265.77

Thus, ROE = (Net Profit / Average Owner's Equity) × 100%  
  = (1,105,265.77 / 13,552,632.89) × 100%  
  ≈ 8.16%

2. Debt to Asset Ratio

This ratio is calculated by dividing total liabilities by total assets. From the balance sheet:
• Total Liabilities (given as Total Current Liabilities) = 1,548,001.20  
• Total Assets at the end = 15,653,266.97

Thus, Debt to Asset Ratio = 1,548,001.20 / 15,653,266.97  
  ≈ 0.0989, which rounds to about 0.10

3. Gross Profit Margin

Gross Profit Margin is given by Gross Profit divided by Total Revenue. From the income statement:
• Gross Profit = 2,620,023.09  
• Total Revenue = 5,760,023.09

Thus, Gross Profit Margin = (2,620,023.09 / 5,760,023.09) × 100%  
  ≈ 45.40%

The final answers are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "8.16%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.10",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "45.40%"
  }
}
